# Windows CMD Commands Only

**CRITICAL RULE: Always use Windows CMD (Command Prompt) syntax for all terminal operations.**

## Required Command Syntax

### ✅ Use These Windows CMD Commands:
- `dir` - List directory contents
- `type filename` - Display file contents  
- `copy source dest` - Copy files
- `move source dest` - Move/rename files
- `del filename` - Delete files
- `rmdir dirname` - Remove directories
- `mkdir dirname` - Create directories
- `cd path` - Change directory
- `ren oldname newname` - Rename files
- `echo text` - Display text
- `cls` - Clear screen

### ❌ NEVER Use These PowerShell Commands:
- `Get-ChildItem` (use `dir` instead)
- `Remove-Item` (use `del` instead)  
- `New-Item` (use `mkdir` or `echo` instead)
- `Set-Location` (use `cd` instead)
- `Rename-Item` (use `ren` instead)
- Any command starting with `Get-`, `Set-`, `New-`, `Remove-`
- Any syntax containing `$_`, `$`, `-ErrorAction`, `ForEach-Object`
- Any PowerShell-specific operators or cmdlets

### File Operations Examples:
```cmd
REM List files
dir

REM Copy file  
copy file1.txt file2.txt

REM Rename file
ren oldfile.txt newfile.txt

REM Delete file
del unwantedfile.txt

REM Create directory
mkdir newfolder

REM Batch rename (use simple FOR loops)
for %%f in (*.html) do ren "%%f" "%%~nf.txt"
```

## Rationale
- Windows CMD commands work universally on all Windows systems
- PowerShell commands can fail due to execution policies or version differences  
- CMD syntax is more predictable and reliable for basic file operations
- Simpler syntax reduces errors in automated operations

**This rule applies to ALL terminal command suggestions in this codebase.**